"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Proverbs chapters 16–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-proverbs-16-18.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/proverbs.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/proverbs.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 16's concentration of divine-sovereignty proverbs (vv1, 2, 4, 7, 9, 33) provides
  some of the richest christological material in the section; the sovereign LORD who
  plans and directs finds its NT fulfillment in the Father's purposeful direction of
  the Son's passion (Acts 4:28).
- 17:15 is one of the sharpest Christological paradoxes in Proverbs: "acquitting the
  wicked and condemning the righteous are both detestable to the LORD" — yet the cross
  appears to do exactly this. The resolution (Christ bearing the condemnation in the
  righteous one's place so the wicked can be justly acquitted) is the heart of the
  substitutionary atonement logic that Paul articulates in Rom 3:25-26.
- 18:10 (Name of the LORD as strong tower) is one of the clearest shadow-connections
  to the NT exaltation of Christ's name (Phil 2:9-11; Acts 4:12).
- For transitional/observational proverbs with no direct Christological content, the
  commentary identifies the theme within the wisdom tradition that the NT carries
  forward through Christ's teaching or person.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The contrast between human planning and the LORD&rsquo;s answer of the tongue reveals a sovereignty over speech itself: the human heart makes its plans, but what the tongue actually says in the decisive moment is the LORD&rsquo;s gift. This finds its christological height in the Incarnate Word — in Christ, the Father&rsquo;s right answer is not merely given through the tongue but <em>becomes</em> the tongue: &ldquo;the words that I say to you I do not speak on my own authority, but the Father who dwells in me does his works&rdquo; (John 14:10). Jesus is the Father&rsquo;s definitive &ldquo;right answer&rdquo; to human questioning (Heb 1:1-2).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theme of divine weighing of the spirits (<em>tokhein ruchot</em>) reveals the LORD as the one who perceives what human self-evaluation conceals: all a man&rsquo;s ways seem pure to himself, but the LORD weighs the inner reality. The NT applies this to Christ: &ldquo;he knew all people and needed no one to bear witness about man, for he himself knew what was in man&rdquo; (John 2:24-25). The divine omniscience of YHWH in this verse is the same omniscience that John presents as Christ&rsquo;s own — the weigher of spirits is now the one who walked among people and read their inner life with perfect accuracy.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The instruction to commit one&rsquo;s work to the LORD for established plans is the wisdom form of the trust-and-rely theme central to the Psalter. In Christ, this commitment reaches its ultimate expression: Jesus committed his entire mission to the Father — &ldquo;not my will but yours be done&rdquo; (Luke 22:42) — and the Father established it permanently in the resurrection. The committed work that Proverbs promises will be established is given its deepest example in the Son who entrusted himself to the one who judges justly (1 Pet 2:23), and whose work was established through the empty tomb.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The claim that the LORD made everything for its purpose — even the wicked for the day of disaster — is the boldest sovereignty statement in Proverbs. Acts 4:27-28 applies exactly this logic to the crucifixion: Herod, Pilate, the Gentiles, and the people of Israel &ldquo;gathered together against your holy servant Jesus&rdquo; to do &ldquo;whatever your hand and your plan had predestined to take place.&rdquo; The wicked who served the day of disaster in the crucifixion fulfilled this Proverbs principle: even opposition to Christ was incorporated into the divine purpose. The cross is the supreme instance of Proverbs 16:4.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The proud heart detestable to the LORD — with the assurance that the proud will not go unpunished — names the root sin that the Incarnation most directly addresses. James 4:6 and 1 Peter 5:5 both quote Proverbs 3:34 (&ldquo;God opposes the proud&rdquo;) to contrast pride with the humility Christ embodied: &ldquo;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death&rdquo; (Phil 2:8). The proud heart that is detestable to the LORD finds its antidote in the Christ who is &ldquo;gentle and lowly in heart&rdquo; (Matt 11:29) — the one who reversed Adam&rsquo;s grasping and took the path of voluntary lowering.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Iniquity being atoned for by <em>chesed</em> and <em>emet</em> (faithful love and truth) is a profound anticipation of the atonement&rsquo;s character. John 1:14 describes the incarnate Word as &ldquo;full of grace and truth&rdquo; — the Greek equivalents of <em>chesed</em> and <em>emet</em>. The atonement accomplished by Christ is precisely the act of <em>chesed ve'emet</em>: the faithful love that does not abandon the covenant people and the truth that does not minimize the reality of sin. Proverbs 16:6 anticipates the atoning character of the cross; John 1:14 names the person in whom that atonement arrived.</p>",
    "7": "<p>When a person&rsquo;s ways please the LORD, even their enemies are made to live at peace with them — a shadow of the peace Christ achieves that surpasses all human enmity. The ultimate fulfillment is the reconciliation accomplished by the cross: &ldquo;through him to reconcile to himself all things, whether on earth or in heaven, making peace by the blood of his cross&rdquo; (Col 1:20). The enemies brought to peace in this verse are not merely human adversaries; in Christ, the enmity between God and humanity is resolved: &ldquo;we were reconciled to God by the death of his Son&rdquo; (Rom 5:10).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme of &ldquo;better a little with righteousness&rdquo; is a wisdom formulation of the kingdom economics that Jesus teaches in the Sermon on the Mount. The beatitude &ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit&rdquo; (Matt 5:3) and &ldquo;do not lay up treasures on earth&rdquo; (6:19) carry the same evaluation: small possession with moral integrity exceeds great wealth obtained unjustly. This is the principle of the kingdom where the one who has given up houses and lands for Christ&rsquo;s sake receives back a hundredfold (Matt 19:29) — the Proverbs evaluation of lesser-but-righteous is confirmed and enlarged in the kingdom calculus.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The human heart plans but the LORD directs the steps — the sovereignty of divine providence over human intention — finds its christological application in Acts 4:28: the plotting of rulers against God&rsquo;s anointed (Ps 2:1-2) became the planned pathway of salvation. The human plans of Pilate, Caiaphas, and Judas were each aiming at their own purposes; the LORD directed those steps to accomplish the cross. This verse&rsquo;s principle — that the LORD takes human planning and redirects it toward his own purpose — is demonstrated most clearly in the passion narrative.</p>",
    "10": "<p>An oracle on the lips of the king whose mouth does not err in judgment is the royal ideal — the king as the mouth of the divine will in judicial matters. This is a shadow of Christ, the ultimate prophetic king whose words are without error: &ldquo;the words that I have spoken to you are spirit and life&rdquo; (John 6:63); &ldquo;heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away&rdquo; (Matt 24:35). Where earthly kings partially embodied this oracle-ideal, Christ embodies it completely: his every word is the direct speech of the one in whom &ldquo;all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden&rdquo; (Col 2:3).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Honest scales and balances belonging to the LORD — all weights his concern — establishes divine justice as the standard against which all human systems of justice are measured. In Christ, the one who is &ldquo;the same yesterday and today and forever&rdquo; (Heb 13:8) is also the one appointed as judge of the living and the dead (Acts 10:42). The divine ownership of the standards of justice in this verse is the same ownership that the NT locates in Christ: he is the righteous judge (2 Tim 4:8) whose standards neither fluctuate nor can be manipulated.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The king&rsquo;s throne made secure by righteousness is a royal theology that anticipates Christ&rsquo;s eternal kingship. Where every human throne, however secure, eventually falls, the Messianic throne is established permanently because it is constituted by righteousness: &ldquo;your throne, O God, is forever and ever; the scepter of your kingdom is a scepter of uprightness&rdquo; (Heb 1:8, quoting Ps 45:6-7). The wicked detestable to kings in this verse finds its inverse in the absolute righteousness of the one who, unlike earthly kings, can never abide wickedness in himself.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Righteous lips as the delight of kings and the love of honest speech is a wisdom observation about the rarity and value of truthful counsel in the court. In Christ, the one who is &ldquo;the truth&rdquo; (John 14:6) embodies what this verse commends: his lips speak only what he hears from the Father (John 8:26), and every word is righteous. The theme of the king who delights in honest speech anticipates the Messianic king of Isa 11:3-4 who will not judge by appearances but with righteousness — the one whose lips themselves are righteous.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The king&rsquo;s wrath as messengers of death and the wisdom of appeasing it is a shadow of the divine wrath that the NT addresses through Christ. Romans 5:9 frames the atonement in exactly these terms: &ldquo;we shall be saved by him from the wrath.&rdquo; The wise person who appeases the king&rsquo;s wrath in this verse anticipates Christ as the propitiation — the one who turns away the divine wrath not by flattery but by absorbing it: &ldquo;he is the propitiation for our sins&rdquo; (1 John 2:2; Rom 3:25).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Life in the light of the king&rsquo;s face and his favor like spring rain anticipates the Messianic blessing of living in Christ&rsquo;s presence. The spring rain (<em>malqosh</em>, the latter rain that finalizes the harvest) as the image for royal favor echoes the Messianic Psalm 72:6 (&ldquo;may he be like rain that falls on the mown grass&rdquo;). The life that comes in the light of the king&rsquo;s face is fulfilled in Christ who said &ldquo;I am the light of the world; whoever follows me will not walk in darkness but will have the light of life&rdquo; (John 8:12).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Wisdom better than gold and understanding better than silver is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s highest valuation of the thing hidden in Christ: &ldquo;in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&rdquo; (Col 2:3). The invitation to choose wisdom over silver is the invitation that Paul extends as the choosing of Christ over all competing goods. Proverbs consistently presents wisdom as incomparably valuable; the NT names the person in whom that incomparable value is concentrated — to gain Christ is to gain the wisdom for which this verse urges the reader to pay everything.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The road of the upright leading away from evil is a shadow of the Way that Christ declares himself to be: &ldquo;I am the way&rdquo; (John 14:6). The upright person&rsquo;s road in Proverbs avoids evil and protects the one who travels it; Christ&rsquo;s Way does this perfectly and permanently. Where the wise person&rsquo;s road in this verse requires the traveler&rsquo;s own keeping (&ldquo;whoever keeps to that road&rdquo;), Christ is himself the road that the Father prepared — the Way that is not a moral achievement but a person who can be received and followed.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Pride goes before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a fall — the structural principle that the NT applies to both Satan and humanity&rsquo;s original sin. Isaiah 14:12-15 traces the Luciferic pride (&ldquo;I will ascend above the heights of the clouds, I will make myself like the Most High&rdquo;) and its catastrophic fall. Adam and Eve&rsquo;s grasping at equality with God follows the same structure. Christ&rsquo;s incarnation is the perfect inversion: he who was in the form of God &ldquo;did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped&rdquo; (Phil 2:6) and took the way of voluntary humiliation — and was therefore exalted. The fall that pride produces is reversed by the exaltation that humility receives.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Better to be humble in spirit with the poor than to share plunder with the proud — the beatitude logic that reverses social hierarchy. Jesus&rsquo; Beatitudes (Matt 5:3-12) make this reversal explicit and personal: &ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.&rdquo; The theme of identification with the poor rather than alliance with the powerful runs through Christ&rsquo;s ministry: he was born to poor parents, associated with the outcasts, and declared himself found among &ldquo;the least of these&rdquo; (Matt 25:40). This verse&rsquo;s preference for humble poverty over proud spoils is the wisdom precursor of the kingdom-values Christ embodied.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Blessed is the one who trusts in the LORD — this beatitude form connects the practical wisdom of handling matters wisely with the theological virtue of trust in YHWH. The blessing in this verse is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s closest approach to the Pauline &ldquo;blessed are those whose lawless deeds are forgiven&rdquo; (Rom 4:7). The trust-in-YHWH that the verse commends finds its NT form in faith in Christ: &ldquo;whoever believes in him will not be put to shame&rdquo; (Rom 10:11). The wise handling of matters and the trust in the LORD are united in the one who is himself &ldquo;the wisdom of God and the power of God&rdquo; (1 Cor 1:24).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The wise in heart being called discerning and pleasant words increasing the ability to learn is a wisdom observation about the social function of good teaching. In Christ, the one whose teaching produced the response &ldquo;no one ever spoke like this man&rdquo; (John 7:46), the quality of pleasant words that increase persuasiveness reaches its zenith. Luke 4:22 records that the people &ldquo;marveled at the gracious words that were coming from his mouth.&rdquo; The wisdom of this verse — that the manner of teaching enables learning — is fulfilled in the Teacher who drew crowds and whose words still teach.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Understanding as a fountain of life to those who have it uses the same life-giving water imagery as John 4:14 and 7:38. The fountain of life (<em>meqor chayyim</em>) in the wisdom tradition is the gift that the wise person possesses; in Christ, the fountain is not merely possessed but is the person himself: &ldquo;the water that I will give him will become in him a spring of water welling up to eternal life&rdquo; (John 4:14). The instruction that fools give being merely folly is the negative counterpart: those who do not draw from Christ, the true fountain, can only produce what this verse calls folly.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The heart of the wise teaching the mouth and adding persuasiveness to its words reflects the inner-to-outer directional flow of genuine wisdom. In Christ, this reaches its fulfillment: the source of his teaching was not human learning but the Father who sent him (&ldquo;my teaching is not mine, but his who sent me,&rdquo; John 7:16). Where the wise person&rsquo;s heart teaches their mouth, Christ&rsquo;s mouth was taught by the Father&rsquo;s own heart: &ldquo;as the Father taught me, I speak these things&rdquo; (John 8:28). The wisdom teaching tradition reaches its terminus in the one whose heart is perfectly aligned with the Father&rsquo;s.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Pleasant words as honeycomb — sweet to the soul and healing to the bones — anticipates the life-giving character of Christ&rsquo;s words. The healing dimension is especially significant: Christ&rsquo;s words healed not only souls but bodies, and the wisdom of this verse&rsquo;s pairing of sweetness-to-soul with healing-to-bones anticipates the holistic salvation that Christ brings. The Beatitudes (Matt 5:3-12) are the supreme example of words that are both sweet to the receptive soul and healing in their effect: they reorient the whole person toward blessing.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The path that seems right to a person but whose end is the way of death is a direct Christological contrast-text: Christ declares himself &ldquo;the way&rdquo; (John 14:6) precisely in distinction from paths that seem right but are not. The ways that seem right are not evil by intention but by misdirection — they are chosen by people who believe they are going toward life. Christ&rsquo;s claim to be the exclusive way to the Father is the claim that all other apparently right paths ultimately end in the death this verse describes. This verse may be the single clearest Christological shadow in Proverbs for the exclusivity of the Way.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A worker&rsquo;s appetite driving him on is a wisdom observation about the creational design of human desire as motivation for productive work. This belongs to the theme of the goodness of ordered labor that creation established and the fall disrupted. In Christ, the new creation restores the relationship between desire and productive labor: the desire for the kingdom — &ldquo;seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness&rdquo; (Matt 6:33) — is the renovated appetite that drives the labor of the new-creation life. The hungry worker of this verse is the image of the one who hungers and thirsts for righteousness (Matt 5:6).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The worthless man who digs up evil and whose words burn like fire is a shadow of the destructive speech that James traces to hell itself: &ldquo;the tongue is a fire&hellip; set on fire by Gehenna&rdquo; (Jas 3:6). The fire-of-words image anticipates the NT diagnosis of corrupt speech as having an infernal origin — it does not merely come from fallen human nature but from the adversary who is a liar from the beginning. Christ&rsquo;s words by contrast are spirit and life (John 6:63): the fire of the worthless man&rsquo;s mouth finds its antithesis in the fire of Pentecost (Acts 2:3), which is a fire that gives life rather than destroys it.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The perverse man stirring conflict and the gossip driving apart close friends reflects the satanic work of division. Jesus names the devil as the one who &ldquo;comes only to steal and kill and destroy&rdquo; (John 10:10) — and division of the community is one of the primary forms of that destruction. Christ&rsquo;s high-priestly prayer (John 17:20-23) is the counter-movement: the prayer for unity is the prayer against the divisive force this verse describes. The gossip who separates close friends typifies the anti-community work that Christ&rsquo;s prayer and death together resist.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The violent man who entices his neighbor down a path that is not good typifies the corrupting influence the wisdom tradition consistently warns against. Christ&rsquo;s warning about &ldquo;false prophets who come to you in sheep&rsquo;s clothing&rdquo; (Matt 7:15) and the millstone pronouncement about those who cause little ones to stumble (Matt 18:6) stand in the tradition of this verse. The enticement toward a not-good path is the work of every false guide; Christ as the true guide declares himself the Good Shepherd who leads on right paths (John 10:11; Ps 23:3).</p>",
    "30": "<p>The one who closes his eyes to scheme perversity and purses his lips to bring evil to pass is the image of deliberate, premeditated wickedness. The wisdom tradition&rsquo;s attention to the physical signs of moral intention anticipates Christ&rsquo;s teaching on the heart as the source: &ldquo;out of the heart come evil thoughts, murder, adultery, sexual immorality, theft, false witness, slander&rdquo; (Matt 15:19). The scheming described in this verse is the external expression of an interior corruption — the problem that Christ addresses at the source by offering the new heart of the new covenant (Ezek 36:26; John 3:3).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gray hair as a crown of glory found on the path of righteousness connects longevity with right-living — an observation within the creational order. The Ancient of Days in Daniel 7:9 (<em>attiq yomin</em>, the one advanced in days) is described with &ldquo;hair like pure wool&rdquo; — the same whiteness that Revelation 1:14 attributes to the risen Christ: &ldquo;the hairs of his head were white, like white wool, like snow.&rdquo; The glorified wisdom of age, here attributed to the person who walks righteously, is taken up in the apocalyptic tradition and applied to the glorified Christ whose white hair is not age but eternal glory.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Slow to anger being better than the mighty, and ruling one&rsquo;s spirit better than capturing a city — the inversion of the warrior ethic in favor of self-mastery — anticipates Christ&rsquo;s self-command in the passion. Pilate marveled that Jesus did not defend himself (Matt 27:14); the one who could have called twelve legions of angels (Matt 26:53) exercised the ultimate self-mastery: not the capture of a city but the absorption of the world&rsquo;s hatred without retaliation. This is the supreme instance of what this verse commends: the strength that does not strike back is greater than the strength that conquers.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The lot cast into the lap but every decision belonging to the LORD is the sovereignty statement that governs every apparent element of chance. The soldiers casting lots for Jesus&rsquo; garments (Matt 27:35; John 19:24) fulfilled Psalm 22:18 — they acted from indifference, but the lot&rsquo;s outcome was the LORD&rsquo;s decision, completing a Scripture written a millennium before. The selection of Matthias by lot (Acts 1:26) operated on the same principle: the church&rsquo;s prayer and the lot&rsquo;s falling were both the LORD&rsquo;s decision. This verse is the theological basis for the early church&rsquo;s confidence that even the apparently random details of the passion were divinely directed.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Better a dry morsel in peace than a house full of feasting with strife — the kingdom-economics reversal at the heart of the wisdom tradition. Jesus embodies this: he had nowhere to lay his head (Matt 8:20), ate with sinners in simple hospitality, and declared blessed those who hunger (Matt 5:6). The peace that exceeds feasting is identified in Philippians 4:7 as &ldquo;the peace of God that surpasses all understanding&rdquo; — the peace that abides even in material poverty. Christ&rsquo;s own life was the living proof that the dry morsel in peace is the better portion.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The wise servant ruling over the shameful son and sharing in the inheritance is a shadow of the reversal of status in Christ&rsquo;s kingdom. The parable of the prodigal son inverts this proverb&rsquo;s scenario in a way that reveals grace: the shamed son is restored by the father&rsquo;s initiative, not simply superseded by the wise servant. But the principle of the wise inheriting what the foolish forfeit governs the NT teaching on sonship and inheritance: those who receive Christ &ldquo;receive the right to become children of God&rdquo; (John 1:12) and share in an inheritance that natural birth cannot guarantee.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The crucible for silver and furnace for gold as the LORD&rsquo;s method for testing hearts is one of the richest metallurgical types in the Scriptures for the refining work of trial. Malachi 3:3 applies this to the Messianic messenger who &ldquo;will sit as a refiner and purifier of silver&rdquo; — a passage that the NT understands as pointing to Christ&rsquo;s purifying ministry. Peter applies the tested-gold metaphor directly to Christian suffering: &ldquo;the tested genuineness of your faith — more precious than gold that perishes though it is tested by fire — may be found to result in praise and glory and honor at the revelation of Jesus Christ&rdquo; (1 Pet 1:7). Christ is both the refiner and the standard of purity that the refining produces.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The evil person&rsquo;s attention to wicked lips and the liar&rsquo;s attention to a destructive tongue identifies the self-selecting feedback loop of moral corruption: we are formed by what we attend to. Christ&rsquo;s teaching on the eye as the lamp of the body (Matt 6:22-23) and Paul&rsquo;s instruction to think about &ldquo;whatever is true, whatever is honorable, whatever is just&rdquo; (Phil 4:8) address the same formative dynamic from the positive direction. This verse&rsquo;s diagnosis — that listening to wicked speech makes the listener more wicked — is the negative form of the principle that listening to Christ makes the listener more Christlike.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Whoever mocks the poor insults his Maker — this identification between the dignity of the person and the dignity of the Creator is the foundation for the NT&rsquo;s identification of Christ with the poor. Matthew 25:40 makes explicit what this verse implies: &ldquo;as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me.&rdquo; To mock the poor is to insult YHWH who made them; to mistreat the poor is to mistreat Christ who identifies with them. The theological logic is the same in both: the creator-creature relationship grounds the dignity of every person, and Christ&rsquo;s solidarity with the poor extends this to its ultimate consequence.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Grandchildren as the crown of the elderly and children finding their glory in their fathers is a wisdom observation about the generational nature of covenant life. In Christ, the generational covenant structure reaches its goal: he is the son of David (Matt 1:1) in whom all the generations of Israel find their crown, and he is the firstborn among many brothers (Rom 8:29) who become children of God through him. The joy of fathers in sons and sons in fathers is redeemed in the relationship between the Father and the Son: &ldquo;this is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased&rdquo; (Matt 3:17).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The unfittingness of fine speech for a fool and lying lips for a ruler is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s insistence that speech must be congruent with character. In Christ, this congruence is absolute: he is the one in whose mouth no deceit was found (1 Pet 2:22; Isa 53:9). Where every human ruler&rsquo;s speech is corrupted to some degree by self-interest and the willingness to mislead, the king of kings speaks only what is true. The lying lips that are unsuitable for a ruler in this verse are the antithesis of the lips of Christ whose every word is truth (John 17:17).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The bribe like a charm stone in the eyes of its user — wherever he turns, success — is an observation about the deceptive power of material influence in human systems. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s realistic observation about how the world actually works, not an endorsement. Christ&rsquo;s kingdom operates by a counter-logic: he refused the offer of all the kingdoms of the world and their glory (Matt 4:8-10), choosing instead the way of the cross. The bribe-charm of this verse is the wisdom form of Satan&rsquo;s offer; Christ&rsquo;s refusal demonstrates that the charm is ultimately illusory.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Covering an offense seeking love and repeated bringing-up of offenses driving apart close friends reflects the covenant-loyalty logic of forgiveness as the foundation of community. 1 Peter 4:8 quotes Proverbs 10:12 (&ldquo;love covers a multitude of sins&rdquo;) in this tradition. In Christ, the covering of offenses is not merely commended but accomplished: he is the propitiation (1 John 2:2), the one whose sacrifice covers the offense completely. The friend who covers the offense in this verse is a type of the friend who &ldquo;laid down his life for his friends&rdquo; (John 15:13) so that the offense need never be brought up again.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A rebuke penetrating more deeply into a wise person than a hundred blows into a fool is a wisdom observation about the role of receptivity in formation. Christ&rsquo;s rebukes of the disciples — &ldquo;O you of little faith&rdquo; (Matt 8:26); &ldquo;get behind me, Satan&rdquo; (Matt 16:23) — were the rebukes that penetrated because they were spoken by the one who knew the inner life of those he rebuked. The wise disciples received these penetrating words; the fool-pattern belongs to those who, like the Pharisees, received endless rebuke without penetration. The disciples who received Christ&rsquo;s rebukes were being formed by them.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The evil man who seeks only rebellion and the merciless messenger sent against him establishes the justice principle that rebellion does not escape consequences. The rebellion against God that all humanity participates in through Adam (Rom 5:12) generates precisely the merciless consequence this verse describes: &ldquo;the wages of sin is death&rdquo; (Rom 6:23). Christ bears that merciless consequence in the place of rebels: &ldquo;while we were enemies we were reconciled to God by the death of his Son&rdquo; (Rom 5:10). The rebel who deserves the merciless messenger finds instead the merciful Savior who absorbs the messenger&rsquo;s blow.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Better to encounter a bear robbed of her cubs than a fool caught in his foolishness — the extreme danger of confronting entrenched folly. This verse does not have a direct Christological connection, but it belongs to the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s warning about the self-destructive trajectory of foolishness that Christ addresses in the parable of the two builders (Matt 7:24-27): the fool builds on sand, and when the storm comes, the destruction is complete. Encountering the fool in his folly is as dangerous as encountering the bear in hers — and as unavoidable when judgment comes.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Whoever returns evil for good — evil will not leave his house — establishes the principle of moral consequence that the passion narrative illuminates in reverse. Humanity returned evil for the good of creation, image-bearing, and covenant, yet Christ absorbed that evil rather than returning it. Romans 12:17-21 uses this exact principle: &ldquo;do not repay anyone evil for evil&rdquo; — grounded in the model of Christ who &ldquo;when he was reviled, he did not revile in return&rdquo; (1 Pet 2:23). The evil that does not leave the house of the evil-for-good-returner is stayed from the house of the one who, like Christ, absorbs it instead.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The start of conflict like a crack letting out water — abandon the dispute before it breaks open — is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s insight into conflict prevention as easier than conflict resolution. Christ as the Prince of Peace (Isa 9:6) and Peacemaker (Col 1:20) operates at the level where the crack is stopped before the dam breaks: the reconciliation he accomplishes is prevenient, addressing the root enmity (the enmity between God and humanity) before it issues in eschatological destruction. The crack in the dam of this verse is the image of unchecked sin; Christ&rsquo;s atonement stops the crack.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Both acquitting the wicked and condemning the righteous are detestable to the LORD — yet the cross appears to do both simultaneously: YHWH condemns the righteous one (the Son) and acquits the wicked (sinners). Romans 3:25-26 provides the theological resolution: the cross demonstrates that God is &ldquo;just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus.&rdquo; The cross does not violate Proverbs 17:15; it fulfills it at a deeper level — the just condemnation falls on Christ, not on the wicked who receive the acquittal. The scales of divine justice are not abandoned but satisfied.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The fool with money to buy wisdom but no desire for it reveals that access to wisdom does not create appetite for it. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s observation about the limits of external provision for internal transformation. Christ&rsquo;s encounter with the rich young man (Matt 19:16-22) illuminates this: the man had access, proximity to the wisdom-teacher himself, yet lacked the desire that would have led him to give up his wealth. The transformation of the will that produces desire for wisdom is the work of the Spirit (Ezek 36:26-27; John 3:5-8) — the provision that goes beyond access to the production of genuine desire.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A friend who loves at all times and a brother born for adversity — this is the most direct wisdom-tradition anticipation of Christ&rsquo;s self-description in John 15:13-15: &ldquo;greater love has no one than this, that someone lay down his life for his friends.&rdquo; The friend who loves not only in prosperity but <em>at all times</em> — including in the hour of adversity — is the pattern of the one who loved his own &ldquo;to the end&rdquo; (John 13:1). The friend born for adversity is the type of Christ born into a world of sin and suffering specifically to be present with humanity in its adversity.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The person lacking good sense who gives a pledge of surety is the financial-folly observation that warns against ill-considered guarantees. This verse does not have a direct Christological connection, but it belongs to the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s concern for prudent stewardship that Jesus addresses in the parables: &ldquo;which of you, desiring to build a tower, does not first sit down and count the cost?&rdquo; (Luke 14:28). The one who gives a pledge without calculating the cost is the same figure as the builder who starts without counting. Wisdom requires the counting that precipitate action skips.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Loving quarreling as loving transgression and raising one&rsquo;s gate courting destruction — the connection between contentious disposition and self-destruction. James 4:1-3 addresses the same connection from the christological angle: wars and quarrels come from desires at war within — the un-submitted desires that the submission to Christ is meant to transform. The one who raises his gate (exalts his entrance, literally) in pride courts the destruction that pride produces (Prov 16:18). The cure for quarreling in the wisdom tradition is the humility that Christ embodies and commands.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The crooked heart finding no good and the perverse tongue falling into trouble identifies the inner-outer connection: the crooked (<em>'iqqesh</em>) heart produces the perverse tongue that leads to self-destruction. This is the diagnostic insight that Christ addresses in Mark 7:20-23: &ldquo;what comes out of a person is what defiles him&rdquo; — evil speech comes from an evil heart. The cure is not behavioral modification of the tongue but the new heart of Ezekiel 36:26 that the Spirit gives through Christ. The perverse tongue that falls into trouble in this verse is the symptom; the crooked heart is the disease that Christ alone can heal.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The grief of the father over a foolish son is a sustained theme in Proverbs that finds its christological reversal in the parable of the prodigal son (Luke 15:11-32). There the father&rsquo;s grief over the foolish son is real (he watches the road), but the ending reverses the proverb&rsquo;s trajectory: the foolish son &ldquo;came to himself&rdquo; and returned, and the father ran to meet him. The father&rsquo;s grief is transformed to joy — the joy of finding what was lost (v32). The parable is the gospel announced through the reversal of this wisdom observation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A joyful heart as good medicine and a crushed spirit drying up the bones establishes the spiritual-physical connection between inner joy and bodily health. Nehemiah 8:10 names the same truth theologically: &ldquo;the joy of the LORD is your strength.&rdquo; In Christ, the one who &ldquo;for the joy that was set before him endured the cross&rdquo; (Heb 12:2), the joyful heart that is medicine is demonstrated in its highest form: the joy that sustained the passion is the medicine for the crushed spirit of every believer. The resurrection is the ultimate healing that the joyful heart of the Son produces.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The wicked man accepting a bribe to pervert justice is the antithesis of the divine justice that Christ establishes. The perversion of justice at Jesus&rsquo; trial (bribed witnesses, Matt 26:59-61; Pilate&rsquo;s capitulation to social pressure, John 19:12-16) is the supreme historical instance of justice perverted by bribery and fear. Yet from within this perversion, the divine justice operated: the unjust verdict became the means of the just atonement. What was perverse in Pilate&rsquo;s court became the foundation of the court where Christ will preside as righteous judge (Acts 17:31).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Wisdom right in front of the understanding person while the fool&rsquo;s eyes wander to the ends of the earth reflects the localized, present nature of genuine wisdom against the distracted restlessness of folly. In Christ, wisdom is not at the ends of the earth but immediately present: &ldquo;the word is near you, in your mouth and in your heart&rdquo; (Rom 10:8, quoting Deut 30:14). The wisdom that is &ldquo;right in front&rdquo; of the discerning person is fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s presence: &ldquo;the kingdom of God is in your midst&rdquo; (Luke 17:21). The fool whose eyes wander to the ends of the earth misses the wisdom that is standing before him.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The foolish son as grief and bitterness to his parents is the domestic pain that the wisdom tradition uses to motivate wisdom-formation. This verse is part of the recurring son-and-parent motif that frames the entire book. In the christological trajectory, it belongs to the wisdom about the deep human need for formation that only Christ ultimately provides: the new birth from above (John 3:3) that makes the disciple a genuine child of God who does not bring grief to the Father. The grief of earthly parents over foolish children points toward the Father who desires children who know him.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The injustice of fining the innocent and striking the noble for acting rightly belongs to the legal-justice tradition that the passion fulfills inverted: Christ, the innocent one, was fined (condemned) and struck for acting rightly — for being the Son who did the Father&rsquo;s will. Isaiah 53:4 describes this as the one who &ldquo;carried our griefs&rdquo; being struck by God and afflicted — the ultimate instance of the injustice this verse identifies as not good. The cross is not merely a human injustice; it is the divine paradox where injustice toward the innocent becomes the instrument of justice for the guilty.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Knowledge restraining words and understanding producing a calm spirit is the wisdom of self-possession — the inner quiet that the wisdom tradition consistently commends. Christ&rsquo;s silence before Pilate and Caiaphas (Matt 26:63; 27:12-14) is the supreme demonstration of this verse: the one who knew all things and could have answered every accusation withheld his words in the hour when restraint was the wiser path. Isaiah 53:7 anticipates this: &ldquo;he opened not his mouth.&rdquo; The restrained words of the knowledgeable person in this verse type the silent wisdom of the Suffering Servant.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Even a fool who stays silent being thought wise is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s humorous observation that silence itself confers apparent wisdom. Christ&rsquo;s silence before his accusers (Matt 27:12-14) was not strategic impression management but the genuine wisdom of knowing when to speak and when not to. The disciples who spoke too quickly (Peter declaring he would never deny, Matt 26:33-35) illustrate the negative side of this verse. The silence of the Servant in Isaiah 53 is the type; the silence of Christ in the passion is the antitype that demonstrates the wisdom that exceeds even the well-timed word.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>Whoever isolates himself pursuing his own desires, disregarding all sound wisdom — this is the warning against the self-referential life that cuts itself off from the community of wisdom-formation. In Christ, the antidote to isolation is his own communal life and prayer: &ldquo;where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them&rdquo; (Matt 18:20); &ldquo;do not neglect to meet together&rdquo; (Heb 10:25). The isolated self-pursuer of this verse is the anti-image of the body of Christ where each member needs the others (1 Cor 12:12-27) and where isolation is recognized as contrary to the design of the new creation community.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The fool who takes no pleasure in understanding but only in self-expression names the disorder of speech divorced from receptivity — the talking that does not learn. This is the Proverbs form of what James 1:19 identifies as the condition to resist: &ldquo;be quick to hear, slow to speak.&rdquo; In Christ, the one who was filled with all wisdom yet took time to ask questions (Luke 2:46) and listen to those he met (John 4:7-26) embodies the counter-pattern: understanding-first, self-expression-after. The fool&rsquo;s self-expression is the anti-image of Christ&rsquo;s attentive, receptive mode of engagement with people.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Wickedness arriving with contempt and disgrace with reproach describes the social ecology of moral corruption: sin brings its own social consequences as attendants. This is the wisdom observation that Paul formulates as sowing and reaping (Gal 6:7-8): the harvest of wickedness includes the contempt and reproach that accompany it. In Christ, the reversal is achieved: the one who bore our reproach and disgrace (Ps 69:7; Rom 15:3) carried the consequences of our wickedness so that those who come to him are not associated with their own wickedness but with his righteousness (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The words of a person&rsquo;s mouth as deep waters and the fountain of wisdom as a flowing stream uses the double water-image for wisdom: deep (inexhaustible) and flowing (continuously fresh). In Christ, both images converge: he is the one from whom &ldquo;rivers of living water will flow&rdquo; (John 7:38), and he offers water that becomes &ldquo;a spring of water welling up to eternal life&rdquo; (John 4:14). The deep-waters-and-flowing-stream of wisdom in this verse is identified in the NT as Christ himself — the inexhaustible depth and the continuously refreshing flow are both attributes of the one who is the wisdom of God (1 Cor 1:24).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Not showing partiality to the wicked by denying justice to the righteous establishes impartial justice as the divine standard. The cross&rsquo;s apparent scandal — the righteous denied justice, the wicked acquitted — is addressed in Romans 3:25-26: God demonstrated his righteousness in the cross by not simply passing over sin. The divine impartiality is not abandoned at the cross but preserved: the righteous one bears the condemnation, the wicked are genuinely acquitted, and the standard of justice is satisfied through the substitution rather than violated by it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The fool&rsquo;s lips walking him into arguments and his mouth calling out for a beating — the self-destructive quality of foolish speech — is the negative form of the life-and-death power of the tongue in v21. The wisdom tradition consistently presents the fool as someone who cannot stop talking his way into worse situations. Jesus&rsquo; silence before Pilate (Matt 27:12-14) is the inverse: the wise person whose silence was itself the most powerful statement. The fool who calls out for a beating through his mouth is the shadow-image of the one who was beaten — not because he spoke foolishly but because he spoke truth that the world could not tolerate.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The fool&rsquo;s mouth as his ruin and his lips as a trap for his life — this self-entrapment through speech describes the mechanism by which the wicked destroy themselves through what they say. Caiaphas&rsquo; pronouncement that &ldquo;it is better for one man to die for the people&rdquo; (John 11:50) is the ironic fulfillment: he spoke to destroy Jesus and spoke more truly than he knew, proclaiming the atonement. His words were a trap — not for Jesus but for the established order he was trying to protect. The wisdom of God uses even the fool&rsquo;s ruinous speech to accomplish its purposes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The words of a gossip as choice morsels sinking into the inner depths identifies the deep-penetration quality of whispered slander: it reaches and reshapes the inner life of those who receive it. In the NT, the destructive tongue is addressed through the community of truthful speech that Christ establishes: &ldquo;speaking the truth in love, we are to grow up in every way into him who is the head, into Christ&rdquo; (Eph 4:15). The counter-word to the gossip&rsquo;s choice morsels is the word of truth that builds up rather than the word of slander that corrupts.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The lazy person in his work being kin to the one who destroys identifies negligence as a form of destruction — the person who does nothing is allied with the person who ruins. This belongs to the theme of faithful stewardship that the parable of the talents (Matt 25:14-30) addresses directly: the servant who buried his talent and did nothing was condemned in the same terms as the one who wasted his resources. Christ&rsquo;s expectation of active, productive stewardship means that the lazy person is not neutral — by failing to build, they participate in the demolition.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The name of the LORD as a strong tower into which the righteous run and are protected — this is one of the most significant shadow-verses for the NT exaltation of Christ&rsquo;s name. Philippians 2:9-11 declares that God gave Christ &ldquo;the name that is above every name&rdquo; so that at the name of Jesus every knee will bow. Acts 4:12 makes the soteriological claim explicit: &ldquo;there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved.&rdquo; The strong tower of YHWH&rsquo;s name in this verse is the type; the name of Jesus is the antitype into which the NT invites all people to run for protection.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The rich man&rsquo;s wealth as a strong city and high wall in his imagination — the imaginary security of material prosperity — is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s counterpoint to v10. Where YHWH&rsquo;s name is an actual strong tower, the rich man&rsquo;s wealth is a strong city &ldquo;in his imagination&rdquo; only. The parallel structure makes the comparison explicit: the righteous run to a real tower; the rich man imagines himself in a secure city. Jesus&rsquo; parable of the rich fool (Luke 12:16-21) is the NT elaboration: &ldquo;fool, this night your soul is required of you.&rdquo; The imaginary security of wealth is exposed when the night comes.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Before destruction the heart is proud, but humility comes before honor — the descending-ascending principle that the NT identifies as the Christ-pattern. Philippians 2:8-9 is the definitive statement: &ldquo;he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross. Therefore God has highly exalted him.&rdquo; The structure of this verse — pride leads to destruction; humility leads to honor — is the universal principle that the Incarnation demonstrates with ultimate precision: the one who voluntarily took the lowest place (humbler than poverty, humbler than servanthood, humbler than death — to the cross) was raised to the highest place.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Answering before listening being folly and disgrace reflects the wisdom of receptivity before response. In Christ, this is embodied in his practice of asking questions before teaching (Mark 8:27-29; Luke 10:26), listening to those who approached him, and discerning what they actually needed rather than what they presented. The disciples who repeatedly misunderstood and answered before listening (Peter in Matt 16:22; the disciples in Luke 9:54) demonstrated the folly this verse warns against. The practice of deep listening is a discipline that Christ modeled and that his Spirit cultivates in the community of his followers.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A man&rsquo;s spirit enduring sickness but not a crushed spirit — the limit of human resilience when the inner life collapses. Isaiah 53:5 describes Christ as &ldquo;crushed for our iniquities&rdquo; — the Hebrew <em>medukka</em> (crushed) is the same root as the broken/crushed spirit of this verse. Christ bore the ultimate crushing of spirit — &ldquo;my soul is very sorrowful, even to death&rdquo; (Matt 26:38); &ldquo;my God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rdquo; (Matt 27:46) — so that the crushed spirits of those who come to him might be healed. He endured the uncureable condition of v14 on behalf of those who cannot bear it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The discerning heart acquiring knowledge and the ear of the wise seeking more of it — the insatiability of wisdom-hunger in those who have tasted wisdom — is a shadow of the Beatitude &ldquo;blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied&rdquo; (Matt 5:6). In Christ, the one who is the source of all wisdom (Col 2:3), the discerning heart&rsquo;s hunger finds its ultimate supply. The seeking ear of the wise is the type of the disciples who sought out Jesus for more teaching (Matt 13:36; Mark 4:10) — wisdom-hunger driving them to the fountain.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A person&rsquo;s gift opening doors and bringing him before important people — the social lubricant function of generosity — is a wisdom observation that the NT radicalizes through the gift of the Spirit. The gift that opens the door before the great is not only the social gift of hospitality and material generosity but the charismatic gifts through which the Spirit brings believers before rulers and kings (Matt 10:18-20). The greatest gift that brings people before the greatest Person is the gift of faith itself — the Spirit&rsquo;s work of bringing sinners before the Father through Christ the door (John 10:9).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The first to state his case seeming right until the other comes and examines him reflects the epistemology of partial information — the first account always seems compelling, but examination reveals complexity. In Christ, the one who bears witness to himself and is witnessed by the Father (John 8:14-18) provides the complete testimony that no human one-sidedness can achieve. The legal epistemology of this verse — wait for the cross-examination — is applied in the NT to the question of Christ himself: his resurrection is the cross-examination that tests every account of who he was and vindicates the claim that he is Lord.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The lot settling disputes and parting the mighty from each other — divine arbitration where human resolution has failed — belongs to the sovereignty theme of 16:33. This verse does not have a strong direct Christological connection, but it participates in the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s submission of final determinations to divine disposal. The selection of Matthias by lot (Acts 1:26) is the NT application: when the human community cannot resolve a question, the disposition belongs to the LORD whose every decision governs the lot&rsquo;s fall.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A brother who has been offended being harder to win back than a fortified city — the depth of relational fracture between those who were once close — is the context for Christ&rsquo;s teaching on forgiveness and reconciliation. Matthew 18:15-22 establishes the protocol for winning back an offended brother: go, reprove, take witnesses, and — when the process works — you have gained your brother. The seventy-seven times forgiveness (v22) addresses exactly the hardness this verse describes: it takes persistent, patient love to scale the walls of the offended brother&rsquo;s fortress. Christ&rsquo;s own reconciliation of humanity to God scaled an even more formidable fortress.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Satisfaction by the fruit of one&rsquo;s words and filled by the produce of one&rsquo;s lips — speech as a productive economy where the speaker eats the harvest of their own words. Christ as the Word who was with God and who spoke the world into being (John 1:1-3) is the supreme instance of speech that produces and satisfies: the words of eternal life (John 6:68) are the words whose fruit feeds those who receive them. The filled satisfaction of v20 is the same as Christ&rsquo;s feeding of the five thousand: from his words and his person proceeds the nourishment that satisfies those who come to him.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Death and life in the power of the tongue — this is the most concentrated statement in Proverbs of the power of speech, and it finds its christological fulfillment in Christ as the life-giving Word. John 5:25: &ldquo;the hour is coming, and is now here, when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who hear will live.&rdquo; The tongue&rsquo;s power over life and death in this verse anticipates the voice of Christ that calls Lazarus from the tomb (John 11:43-44) and will call the dead from their graves at the last day (John 5:28-29). The ultimate exercise of the tongue&rsquo;s life-and-death power is the voice of the resurrection.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Finding a wife finding a good thing and receiving favor from the LORD — this marriage-blessing verse participates in the covenant-marriage typology that the NT applies to Christ and the church. Ephesians 5:25-32 makes the marriage a type of Christ&rsquo;s love for the church, explicitly: the finding of the wife by the husband types the finding and loving of the church by Christ. The favor of the LORD in finding a wife types the blessing poured out on the union between Christ and his bride (Rev 19:7-9). What is a blessing in the wisdom tradition becomes in Paul&rsquo;s typology the human shadow of the ultimate nuptial mystery.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The poor speaking with pleas and the rich answering harshly — the social asymmetry of speech where economic standing determines register — is addressed in the NT&rsquo;s radical leveling in Christ. James 2:1-9 directly addresses the partiality toward the rich that this verse describes, grounding the prohibition in the fact that God &ldquo;chose those who are poor in the world to be rich in faith&rdquo; (v5). Christ himself &ldquo;though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor&rdquo; (2 Cor 8:9) — he took the position of the pleading poor, so that all who come to him are heard with the same regard regardless of social standing.</p>",
    "24": "<p>There are companions who lead to ruin, but there is a friend who sticks closer than a brother — the contrast between the many companions of empty friendship and the one true friend. This is the most direct wisdom-type of Christ&rsquo;s self-identification as the Friend in John 15:13-15: &ldquo;you are my friends if you do what I command you.&rdquo; The friend who sticks closer than a brother is the one who loves at all times (Prov 17:17), who is born for adversity, and who lays down his life. The many companions who lead to ruin are the type of false teachers and misleading associations; Christ is the type of the one friend whose closeness exceeds family itself.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'proverbs', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in PROVERBS.values())
    parts = ', '.join(f'ch{ch}={len(PROVERBS[ch])}' for ch in sorted(PROVERBS, key=int))
    print(f'Proverbs 16-18 mkt-christ: {total} verses written ({parts}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
